    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Index This</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Michael Leviton letter holds John C Bogle's July 30 letter on end of contest comparing results of mutual fund portfolios managed by five Vanguard Index 500 fund investment advisers failed to consider tax implications</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Only two things were wrong with John C. Bogle's response to the end of the contest that compared the results of mutual fund portfolios managed by five investment advisers with the Vanguard Index 500 fund (''The Winner Is. . .Indexing,'' Letters, July 30).</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Only two things were wrong with John C. Bogle's response to the end of the contest that compared the results of mutual fund portfolios managed by five investment advisers with the Vanguard Index 500 fund (''The Winner Is. . .Indexing,'' Letters, July 30).</p>
        <p>First, Mr. Bogle did not take into account tax implications. (This would have made the gap between index investing and funds even larger.)</p>
        <p>And second, the letter should have appeared on the front page.</p>
        <p>MICHAEL LEVITON  Hockessin, Del., July 30</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
